@owner: TrellisProject
@stability: experimental
@since: 2026-05-09
@reviewed: 2026-05-10

Feature: Dependency Graph
  "Builds the resolved Provides/Consumes graph and exposes the four core whitepaper queries."

  Provides:
    - graph.Build
    - graph.Graph
    - graph.Edge
    - graph.UnresolvedConsume
    - graph.Graph.ProvidersOf
    - graph.Graph.Lookup
    - graph.Graph.Deps
    - graph.Graph.Dependents
    - graph.Graph.Downstream
    - graph.Graph.Orphans
    - graph.Graph.DuplicateProvides

  Consumes:
    - graph.Sidecar
    - graph.Entry
    - graph.Handle

  Invariants:
    - A Consumes handle MUST resolve to every Sidecar whose Provides contains an equal handle (multi-resolution → multiple edges)
    - A Consumes handle with no matching Provides MUST be recorded as UnresolvedConsume, never silently dropped
    - Self-edges (a Sidecar consuming what it provides) MUST be emitted; the linter decides whether to warn
    - Build MUST NOT mutate input Sidecar values
    - All slices and maps returned by query methods SHALL be treated as read-only by callers
    - DuplicateProvides MUST use exact handle equality only — fuzzy matching is an explicit non-goal here

  OutOfScope:
    - Source-file existence verification (orphan-by-missing-source is a different signal at a higher layer)
    - Fuzzy duplicate detection (whitepaper §4.4 — deferred indefinitely at the graph layer)
    - Mutation API (insert / remove sidecars after Build)

  Scenario (happy-path): Single resolved edge
    Given two sidecars, one Provides 'Foo.bar' and one Consumes 'Foo.bar'
    When Build runs
    Then the resulting Graph has exactly one Edge from consumer to producer

  Scenario (happy-path): Reverse lookup
    Given a graph with an edge from A to B
    When Dependents is called on B
    Then the returned slice contains an Edge whose From is A

  Scenario (negative): Unresolved consume
    Given a Sidecar that Consumes a handle no other sidecar provides
    When Build runs
    Then the Graph's Unresolved list contains exactly that pair (sidecar, handle)
    And no Edge is created for it

  Scenario (edge): Multiple providers of one handle
    Given two sidecars Provide the same handle and one sidecar Consumes it
    When Build runs
    Then the consumer has two outbound edges, one to each provider
    And DuplicateProvides reports that handle

  Scenario (edge): Orphan provider
    Given a Sidecar that Provides 'Lonely.func' which no other sidecar Consumes
    When Orphans is called
    Then the returned slice includes that Sidecar

  Scenario (happy-path): Downstream reaches transitive dependents
    Given a chain A → B → C of resolved Consumes/Provides edges
    When Downstream is called on A
    Then the result contains both B and C
    And B appears before C (BFS order; closer dependents first)

  Scenario (edge): Downstream tolerates cycles
    Given a graph with a cycle A → B → A
    When Downstream is called on A
    Then the result is finite and each sidecar appears at most once

  Scenario (negative): Empty Provides is not orphaned
    Given a Sidecar with zero Provides entries
    When Orphans is called
    Then that Sidecar MUST NOT appear in the result (different lint signal)
